            &lt;p class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;Nobel Peace Prize Medal.&lt;/b&gt; Image by &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Jonathunder&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Jonathunder&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Nobel_Prize.png&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Wikimedia Commons&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;No, that title is not a typo. Nor is it click-bait. It&#39;s actually true. The Nobel Peace Price is usually given to individuals  and sometimes to organizations that promote peace. But this year, Minneapolis, Minnesota, and its residents have collectively been nominated for the 2026 Nobel Peace Prize.&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;Nominations were open until January 31, and will be reviewed by the Norwegian Nobel Committee through September. The winner will be announced in October, and the aware ceremony will be held in December.&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;blockquote&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;[Minneapolis] has met and exceeded the committee&#39;s standard of promoting democracy and human rights, and work aimed at creating a better organized and more peaceful world.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;[The people of Minneapolis have] suffered countless abuses, including harassment, detention, deportation, and injury.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;[In response to these incidents, Minneapolis leaders called for] nonviolent protest, in accordance with the U.S. Constitutionâ€™s promise that Americans have a right to assemble and petition for the redress of grievances.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;figcaption class=&quot;blockquote-footer&quot;&gt;Letter to the Norwegian Nobel Committee from &lt;i&gt;The Nation&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;
