        &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;div class=&quot;blob-content&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;image-right&quot; style=&quot;width:225px&quot;&gt;
                &lt;img class=&quot;img-link&quot; alt=&quot;Fraud Alert&quot; loading=&quot;lazy&quot; decoding=&quot;async&quot; style=&quot;--img-width:200&quot; src=&quot;/images/ggY82mUnbo-200.webp&quot; width=&quot;200&quot; height=&quot;141&quot;&gt;
                &lt;p class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Image by &lt;a href=&quot;https://pixabay.com/users/geralt-9301/?utm_source=link-attribution&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=image&amp;utm_content=464641&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Gerd Altmann&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a href=&quot;https://pixabay.com//?utm_source=link-attribution&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=image&amp;utm_content=464641&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Pixabay&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;
            &lt;div&gt;
                &lt;p&gt;Homeland Security has spent more than $200 million of taxpayer funds to film a television ad featuring Cosplay Barbie Kristi Noem at Mount Rushmore. The law requires the government to engage in a competitive bidding process that is intended to prevent corrupt politicians from awarding government contracts exclusively to their own businesses or their cronies.&lt;/p&gt;
                &lt;p&gt;But Noem&#39;s Homeland Security department bypassed that law on the frequently-disproven claim that immigration constitutes a &quot;national emergency&quot; and awarded the contract so that one of the beneficiaries was a consulting firm with personal and business ties to Noem. Then they hid that information from public records about the contract by listing a phantom company that was formed just days before the deal was finished.&lt;/p&gt;
                &lt;p&gt;Whether or not there is a national emergency that forgoes the need for competitive bidding, the law is very clear in forbidding conflicts of interest in government contracts.&lt;/p&gt;
